Asset Management and Document Types Documentation
This guide covers asset management, procurement processes, policies, compliance, and documentation types essential for IT operations. These ensure tracking, security, and efficient handling of resources and incidents.

Asset Management
Maintain records of all organizational assets for support and financial purposes.
Assets Include: Laptops, desktops, servers, routers, switches, cables, fiber modules, tablets, etc.
Support Integration: Associate tickets with specific device make/model for detailed troubleshooting.
Financial Aspects: Track make/model, configuration, purchase date, location, depreciation, and audits.
Tagging: Add asset tags like barcodes, RFID, visible numbers, or organization names for identification.

Asset Database
Centralized system for tracking assets across the organization.
Usage: Shared by departments for assignments and monitoring.
User Association: Link assets to assigned users for tracking.
Warranty Tracking: Differentiate processes for in/out-of-warranty items.
Licensing: Manage software costs and renewal deadlines.

Procurement Life Cycle
Structured process for acquiring goods and services.
Initiation: Start with user requests, including budgeting and approvals.
Negotiation: Discuss terms with suppliers, covering purchase, invoicing, and payment.
Execution: Handle the financial and logistical aspects of procurement.

Acceptable Use Policies (AUP)
Define acceptable use of company assets to limit liability.
Coverage: Internet, telephones, computers, mobile devices, etc.
Purpose: Detailed rules (often in Rules of Behavior) to protect against misuse; used for disciplinary actions.
Legal Role: Reduces organizational liability in disputes.

Network Topology Diagram
Visual representation of network layout.
Types: Logical diagrams or physical rack layouts.
Purpose: Illustrates connections and locations for planning and troubleshooting.

Compliance
Adherence to laws, policies, and regulations.
Scope: Industry-specific or situational rules; domestic/international.
Consequences: Penalties like fines, job loss, or incarceration.
Importance: Ensures legal and operational standards are met.

Splash Screens
Messages or graphics displayed during startup/login.
Uses: Branding, compliance requirements, or informational notices (e.g., maintenance alerts).
Legal/Admin Purposes: Warnings about misuse or data reliance.

Incident Reports
Document security incidents for policy enforcement.
Requirement: Ongoing documentation for security policies.
Process: Formal plans for incidents; detailed reports for reference and future prevention.

Standard Operating Procedures
Defined processes for business objectives.
Examples: Downtime notifications, facilities issues, software installations/upgrades with testing and change control.
Benefit: Clear documentation for review and understanding by all.

On-Boarding
Process for integrating new employees.
Checklist: New user setup, including IT agreements (e.g., AUP in handbook).
Actions: Create accounts, assign groups/departments, provide preconfigured hardware like laptops/tablets.

Off-Boarding
Process for employee departure.
Checklist: Predefined steps for termination.
Considerations: Hardware return, data handling, account deactivation (not always deletion).

Knowledge Base and Articles
Repositories for solutions and information.
Sources: External (manufacturer KB, communities) or internal (institutional knowledge, help desk software).
Functionality: Searchable archives; automatic searches based on ticket keywords for quick resolutions.
